<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Living Streets (CYS0037)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Living Streets (CYS0037)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are the national charity that stands up for pedestrians. With our supporters we work to create safe, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">attractive and enjoyable streets, where people want to walk. We work with communities, professionals and politicians to make sure every community can enjoy vibrant streets and public spaces.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We started life in 1929 as the Pedestrians Association and have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been the national voice for pedestrians throughout our history. In the early years, our campaigning led to the introduction of the driving test, pedestrian crossings and 30 mph speed limits. Since then our ambition has grown. Today we influence decision ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">kers nationally and locally, run successful projects to encourage people to walk and provide specialist consultancy services to help reduce congestion and carbon emissions, improve public health, and make sure every community can enjoy the benefits of walk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Background</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Streets believes that safety for all road users and particularly the most vulnerable is of paramount importance. For a significant period of time the numbers of people killed and seriously injured on our roads was decreasing however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> during 2011 there was an increase in both pedestrian and cyclist killed and serious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly injured</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> casualties (KSIs). Whilst it is not fully understood why the increase in KSIs happened in 2011 it is important to take note that there has been a substantial increase in the number of cyclists which accounts to some degree for the increase in the number a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd risk of further casualties. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The increase in cycling fatalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">continued</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 2012 by 10% whilst the numbers of pedestrians killed decreased by 7% compared to 2011 although the number seriously injured pedestrians increased by 2%</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Worryingly, this growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> popularity of cycling has not been backed by measures to create a safer cycling environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As a result some new cyclists are now too scared to cycle on our roads perhaps due to lack of infrastructure, anti-social motorised vehicle driver behaviou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r, traffic speeds or lack of confidence. Instead, they choose to cycle on the pavements causing great distress in particular to older or infirm pedestrians. In some cases, evidenced anecdotally by some of our supporters in London, pavement cycling can resu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lt in contributing to the isolation of some people as they may fear being hit by a cyclist whilst walking down their street which causes them to decide not to leave their home. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">What can central and local Government do to improve cycle safety</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Stree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts is extremely concerned by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recent spate of cycling and pedestrian fatalities in London which included three pedestrian fatalities in one day on Friday 16 November. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Streets is supportive of efforts to encourage people to make active travel choi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ces such as walking and cycling and safety for vulnerable road users is paramount to encouraging people to make these choices. We share many of the same objectives as organisations that promote cycling including improving road safety, the environment, air </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quality and promoting a healthy lifestyle. Many of the barriers to cycling and potential solutions are often the same for walking such as slower speeds and better street design However, it is important to note that they remain different travel modes with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">istinctive needs and characteristics. We believe that both walking and cycling have a role to play in increasing active travel journeys and that walking should be the natural choice for shorter journeys and cycling for journeys of two miles or more. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the ways to improve the experience for both cyclists and pedestrians is to plan and implement better street design, which includes a fair allocation of space. In using the road user hierarchy, as outlined in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Manual for Streets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the pedestrian is placed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">first, followed by the cyclist. This therefore ensures a win-win situation meaning that cyclists are provided with adequate road space, meaning less confident cyclists feel they have a share of the road, as well as not making the pedestrian experience any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">worse. It is vital that investment in cycling infrastructure should at the least not make it worse for the pedestrian but at best should improve the pedestrian experience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Living Streets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reducing vehicle speeds on Britainâ€™s streets is the single biggest measure to transforming our streets into safe, people-centred streets, rather than simply corridors for traffic. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Evidence has shown that where 20 mph has been introduced there has been a d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecrease in the number of people killed or seriously injured including amongst cyclists </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pedestrians.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A pedestrian struck at 20mph has a 97% chance of survival, at 30mph the figure is 80%. There is strong public support for 20mph limits as demonstrated b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y a recent Living Streets campaign encouraging supporters to write to local authorities which saw nearly 10,000 people write to their local coun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cillor asking them to support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20 mph speed limits on local authority controlled streets w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here people live, work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and shop.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The adoption of strict liability in the UK would make a difference. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">civil liability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">framework in the UK currently discriminates against vulnerable road users. As it stands, drivers are presumed not liable for damages in the event of a collis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ion with a pedestrian or cyclist. This is in contrast to most of the countries in the rest of the EU, where the burden of proof falls upon the driver to demonstrate that they were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at fault in such collisions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A range of measures including improved vehi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cle design, training and enforcement is also required to increase the safety of vulnerable road users. This includes safer lorries by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopting national best practice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensuring all large vehicles are fitted with blind spot cameras and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> side alarms and by improving driver behaviour through training backed up by better law enforcement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is particular important that enforcement takes place on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">illegal behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Brake has recently highlighted that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more than half a million UK drivers (57</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5,000) have points on their licence for using their mobile phone at the wheel or being otherwise distracted. In a large-scale study of commercial drivers, which monitored the impact of them texting at the wheel, their crash risk increased to 23 times that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of a driver paying full attention.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that there needs to be political will and ministerial leadership to increase the number of people cycling and walking. Living Streets believes that the Government needs to set out a clear vision that enables p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lanners to reallocate road space from the motor vehicle in favour of cyclists and pedestrians. This vision needs to be backed by policy and embedded in business plans across Government departments, such as, the Department for Transport, Department of Healt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h and Department for Education. The policy approach should be to identify and eliminate structural barriers to walking and cycling, for example, by making it easier to implement 20 mph limits. This would complement the cross disciplinary approach engendere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d by transfer of responsibility for public health to local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorities. Furthermore, the Government should follow the example in Wales of the Active Travel (Wales) Act.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reported-road-casualties-great-britain-annual-report-2012"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reported-road-casualties-great-britain-annual-report-2012</span></a></p></body></html>